    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nNeovim has started making a folder in my home directory called `.vim` that seems \r\nto store the neovim swap files instead of in `$XDG_CACHE_HOME/nvim`\r\n\r\nI've never had this happen before and I haven't found anyone else have this happen either.\r\n\r\nI tried backing up my config, deleting it, and making a sample file \r\nwith some keyboard spam and it still makes the directory.\r\n\r\nI have not modified my `$XDG_CACHE_HOME` variable, so I know that's not the problem\r\n\r\nMy temporary solution is that I've made an immutable `.vim` directory in `~` to force \r\nNeovim to use `$XDG_CACHE_HOME/nvim`,  but I would rather my `~` not be dirty\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\nnvim *any file*\r\n\r\n*write anything to said file*\r\n\r\n:wq\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nI expect it to put any swap files into `$XDG_CACHE_HOME/nvim`\r\n\r\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\n0.9.1\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nI don't have vanilla vim installed\r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\narchlinux 2023.07.01\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\nkitty 0.29.2\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\nxterm-kitty\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\nsystem package manager (pacman)",
